Hiya, We care about the welfare of animals used to produce our meat. For all Co-op brand meat and poultry, we donâ€™t allow the use of antibiotics, unless there is written approval of a vet to address a specific health issue with the animal. 1/3

We also donâ€™t allow the preventive use of antibiotics within our supply chain. All our own-brand chicken is 100% British, reared to Red Tractor standards and our premium range chicken meets RSPCA Assured standards. 2/3

In addition to our own strict welfare standards, monitored through our own dedicated Chicken Farming Group. We constantly review how we source products and continue to follow the progress of the European Chicken Commitment closely.  3/3
^Lis

We launched an Action on Plastics plan within our Future of Food 2030 ambition in September 2018, pledging that:
1.All Co-op own-brand packaging will be possible to recycle from June 2020, at home or through the collection of plastic film in selected Co-op stores. 3/4
We only stock 100% British chicken and chlorinated chicken is banned under UK legislation. There are no plans to change our sourcing standards. ^Graham

2. We will use a min of 50% recycled plastic in PET bottles, pots, tubs, trays & HPDE bottles by 2021.
3. Eliminated all dark & black plastic packaging from our OB range (in Dec 2019) & we are working on plans to eliminate CPET and replace it with a widely recycled material. 3/5

4.We will eliminate Co-op own-brand plastic products not designed to be recycled or reused from June 2023.
5.We will work with partners to improve recycling rates and help customers reuse and recycle products designed for that purpose easily

Hi. We know that plastics and packaging are as much of a concern for members and customers as they are for us. Although we donâ€™t have all the solutions yet, we hope to inspire change and bring together the industry and shoppers, because we need to work together to get results (1)

We were one of the first retailers to highlight the plastics problem back in 2016 when we published our Co-op Tipping Point Report. Historically, weâ€™ve always pushed plastics innovation, launching the first UK supermarket certified compostable carrier bag in 2008 and changing (2)

our cotton bud stems to cardboard 11 years before other UK retailers.
We launched an Action on Plastics plan within our Future of Food 2030 ambition in September 2018, pledging that:
1. All Co-op own-brand packaging will be possible to recycle from June 2020, at home or (3)

or through the collection of plastic film in selected Co-op stores.
2. We will use a minimum of 50% recycled plastic in PET bottles, pots, tubs, trays and HPDE bottles by 2021.
3. We have eliminated all dark and black plastic packaging from our OB range (in Dec 2019) and we (4)

are working on plans to eliminate CPET and replace it with a widely recycled material.
4. We will eliminate Co-op own-brand plastic products not designed to be recycled or reused from June 2023.
5. We will work with partners to improve recycling rates and help customers reuse (5)

reuse and recycle products designed for that purpose easily.

Co-op has always been at the forefront of removing hidden plastic on own-brand products where we can, removing unnecessary packaging, from removing plastic from cotton (6)

cotton buds 11 years ago, banning microbeads and removing plastic straws. We are committed to making all our own brand packaging possible to recycle or reusable from June 2020. We have set a plastic reduction target of 6% over the next 2 years, using 2018 as the baseline.(7) ^Ian

Hi,
Co-op is reducing  use of plastic on  own-brand packaging where possible, and where we do use it, packaging will be possible to recycle from  2020, at home or through the collection of plastic film in selected Co-op stores.
We are achieving this by improving recyclability
(moving packaging to Easy to Recycle by OPRL standard), increasing recycled content, and changing materials to remove plastic altogether.

This applies to packaging, plastic items, and plastics in products that you may not know is there.

Removing food packaging can have unintended consequences on product quality and shelf-life, resulting in increased food waste.
This is why Co-op will only use plastic on its own brand packaging where it has a demonstrable benefit to these things.  Thanks ^Andrea
